{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 12:27:48.505905", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos (fat‑tree) lab\\nSummary\\n- Control plane (EBGP/FRR) appears healthy: all routers advertise and have routes for the two host subnets (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) with expected next‑hops.\\n- Data plane between the two hosts is impaired: substantial packet loss and asymmetric reachability between pc_0_0 and pc_0_1.\\n- Problem localized to pc_0_1 (host) and its access link toward leaf_router_0_1 (leaf_router_0_1:eth2). Root cause is evidence of deliberate/accidental packet corruption on pc_0_1 (netem qdisc showing 60% corruption) which manifests as RX drops on the leaf.\\n\\nDetails and evidence\\n\\n1) Host-level reachability tests\\n- From pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1:\\n  - ping: 4 transmitted, 2 received, 50% packet loss; rtt avg ≈ 3.22 ms\\n  - Evidence: \"4 packets transmitted, 2 received, 50% packet loss\"\\n- From pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0:\\n  - ping attempt timed out (command exceeded timeout) — indicates severe or total packet loss in that direction from pc_0_1.\\n  - Evidence: \"[TIMEOUT] Command \\'ping -c 4 10.0.0.2\\' on \\'pc_0_1\\' exceeded 10s.\"\\n\\n2) Host and interface configuration\\n- pc_0_0:\\n  - eth0: 10.0.0.2/24, qdisc = fq_codel (normal)\\n  - default route via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0)\\n- pc_0_1:\\n  - eth0: 10.0.1.2/24, qdisc = netem (nonstandard)\\n  - default route via 10.0.1.1 (leaf_router_0_1)\\n  - Evidence: ip addr shows \"eth0 ... inet 10.0.1.2/24 ... qdisc netem\"\\n\\n3) netem / traffic control statistics (highly relevant)\\n- get_tc_statistics on pc_0_1: shows qdisc netem with \"corrupt 60%\".\\n  - Evidence: \"qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%\".\\n  - Interpretation: 60% of packets are being intentionally marked/corrupted by the qdisc — consistent with very high packet loss and failed pings.\\n\\n4) Leaf router access interface RX drops\\n- leaf_router_0_1 (the leaf serving pc_0_1) ifconfig:\\n  - eth2 (10.0.1.1): RX packets 14 bytes..., RX errors 0 dropped 3\\n  - Evidence: \"eth2 ... RX packets 14 ... RX errors 0 dropped 3\"\\n  - Interpretation: The leaf is observing dropped RX packets on its access interface; consistent with corrupted or invalid packets arriving from pc_0_1.\\n\\n5) Control plane / routing (FRR) state\\n- BGP routes for the host prefixes are present across routers; next-hops align with the expected topology:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 routes: 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 (spine_router_0_0)\\n    - Evidence: \"B>* 10.0.1.0/24 [20/0] via 172.16.0.4, eth0\"\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 routes: 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.10 (spine_router_0_1)\\n    - Evidence: \"B>* 10.0.0.0/24 [20/0] via 172.16.0.10, eth1\"\\n  - Spines and super‑spine show learned routes to both /24s; no missing prefixes observed.\\n- Interpretation: The routing fabric is converged and advertising the host subnets — control plane is NOT the primary cause.\\n\\nLocalization and likely root cause\\n- Localized components:\\n  - Primary: pc_0_1 (host) — netem qdisc configured and reporting \"corrupt 60%\".\\n  - Secondary manifestation: leaf_router_0_1:eth2 — observed RX drops (dropped 3 packets).\\n- Root cause (most likely): packet corruption induced at the host qdisc on pc_0_1 (netem corrupt 60%) is corrupting or discarding a large fraction of packets. This produces high packet loss and asymmetric failure for flows between pc_0_1 and pc_0_0; the leaf sees the consequence as RX drops on the access interface.\\n- Confidence: high — the presence of \"netem ... corrupt 60%\" on pc_0_1 directly explains the observed data‑plane symptoms and correlates with interface RX drops on the leaf.\\n\\nImpact\\n- Host-to-host connectivity between pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 is unreliable:\\n  - Up to ~50% loss observed in one direction; the other direction failed entirely within test timeout.\\n- Control plane (BGP) and inter‑router forwarding appear healthy and intact; no evidence of route withdrawal or BGP flaps for the host prefixes.\\n\\nAdditional observations (non-critical)\\n- Routes and next-hops shown by FRR are consistent with topology; next-hop selection sometimes funnels through one spine from the super‑spine (this is a normal BGP path choice given the lab).\\n- Packet latencies for successful pings were low (~3 ms), indicating no widespread congestion/latency issues on forwarding paths.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Network control plane is healthy and converged.\\n- The observed data-plane failure between hosts is due to host-local packet corruption on pc_0_1 (netem corrupt 60%), causing packet loss and resulting RX drops at leaf_router_0_1:eth2. This is the root cause of the host connectivity issues.\\n\\n(End of diagnostic report), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='be9b770d-6c9c-4fcf-afff-b5cd54778d7f'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
